    "body": "As @jinhojang6 mentioned, Lokalise can only be connected to a single repo. There is a webhook that reflects all the files from [status-react translations](https://github.com/status-im/status-react/tree/develop/translations), these files get updated (manually) periodically with new translations from Lokalise. That implies Desktop .ts files can't be reflected via webhook in the current Lokalise project. One of the options is to [create a separate Lokalise project for Desktop translations only](https://github.com/status-im/status-desktop/issues/4759#issuecomment-1124807142), but it's not really an option, because Mobile and Desktop are supposed to share many same translatable strings and we expect translations for them to be exactly the same. The second option is to convert .ts files via script to .json and keep only one [status-react translations](https://github.com/status-im/status-react/tree/develop/translations) repo, as shown [here](https://github.com/status-im/status-desktop/issues/4759#issuecomment-1032689043).\r\n\r\nIn order to get around the above and take advantage of Lokalise multiplatform translations support and avoid custom scripting we should consider:\r\na) creating separate repo for all platforms, that is: status-im/status-clients-translations which will contain both .ts and .json files (still merging the keys requires manual action I believe)\r\nb) making the process of updating .ts files and merging keys manual, as described here: https://github.com/status-im/status-desktop/blob/6c2b2aa2846400f7afcc98777c8e800d99ca8cc6/I18N.md#tldr\r\n\r\nI and @jinhojang6 both prefer option a)\r\n\r\nCC: @jrainville @hesterbruikman @John-44 ",
